reviews.review_text: must have who ever reads this review get the show and the rest of the wharfield run 5.5.5

Warfield The recording sounds kind of hollow not near as good as a sound board recording. Lots of crowd noise at times too. 
On the other hand the band is playing well, Jerry's vocals are great and I love the accoustic sets. 
Check out the sound board recordings of the warfield and the following Radio City Music hall shows.

Bursts of insanity The electric sets didn't always measure up to the delight of the acoustic sets; that's OK.  But there is a nice bit of crazed, manic intensity from Althea , Jack Straw, Deal, China Cat, I Know You Rider.  Blistering solos and careening chaos just rolling off the stage.  The audience recording gives you the feeling of the intensity of a downhill, runaway locomotive.  The acoustic quality is a little thin; listen to the board for that.  The electric quality is better; a few technical glitches along the way.
Great first show Incredible show. These 1980 acoustic/electric/electric shows at the Warfield, Saegner and Radio City are some of my fave Dead shows and one of my fave Dead runs period.
- Way too crowd-heavy a recording to listen to loud enough to hear what they're playing.

Grateful for the taper The quality of the recording improves.  Yes, the first song has some issues.  If I recall correctly, there was no official taping section until after Greek Theatre run of 1984.  So, given the fact that this would have been a stealth recording, my hat is off to you.  Yes, I did listen to the soundboard of the acoustic set first, then I cam here.  All told, we are lucky to have this recording to document the opening night of the Warfield / Radio City run of 1980.
